# xv6 Lottery Scheduler

Submission-ready xv6-riscv implementation of a lottery scheduler for CSE 321
Lab Assignment 2.

This project replaces xv6's default round-robin scheduler with lottery
scheduling. Runnable processes receive CPU time probabilistically according to
their ticket counts, and each process tracks how many scheduling rounds it has
received.

## Assignment Coverage

| Requirement | Status |
| --- | --- |
| Add `tickets` and `rounds` to `struct proc` | Complete |
| Initialize tickets and rounds for new processes | Complete |
| Give `init` 10 tickets | Complete |
| Inherit tickets across `fork()` | Complete |
| Add `settickets(int n)` syscall | Complete |
| Use the specified pseudorandom generator | Complete |
| Replace round-robin with lottery scheduling | Complete |
| Increment `rounds` on each scheduler selection | Complete |
| Print rounds in `procdump()` / `Ctrl+P` | Complete |
| Add `test_scheduler` user program | Complete |

## Key Files

| File | Purpose |
| --- | --- |
| `kernel/proc.h` | Adds `tickets` and `rounds` to each process |
| `kernel/proc.c` | Implements random generation, lottery scheduling, inheritance, and `procdump()` output |
| `kernel/sysproc.c` | Implements `sys_settickets()` |
| `kernel/syscall.h` | Adds the syscall number |
| `kernel/syscall.c` | Registers the syscall handler |
| `user/user.h` | Exposes `settickets(int)` to user programs |
| `user/usys.pl` | Generates the user syscall stub |
| `user/test_scheduler.c` | Test program for lottery proportions |
| `SUBMISSION.md` | Exact file-by-file patch notes and full required code blocks |

## Run

Build and boot xv6:

```sh
make qemu
```

Inside xv6, start test processes with different ticket counts:

```sh
test_scheduler 10 &
test_scheduler 5 &
test_scheduler 2 &
```

Press `Ctrl+P` multiple times. The `rounds` values should grow roughly in
proportion to the ticket ratio, for example `10:5:2`.

Expected output shape:

```text
1 sleep  init 32
2 sleep  sh 18
5 runble test_scheduler 110
6 runble test_scheduler 55
7 run   test_scheduler 22
```

## Submission Notes

`SUBMISSION.md` contains the exact file modifications, insertion points,
complete code blocks, test commands, expected behavior, and final checklist
required for patch submission.

## Upstream xv6 Notes

xv6 is a re-implementation of Dennis Ritchie's and Ken Thompson's Unix
Version 6 (v6).  xv6 loosely follows the structure and style of v6,
but is implemented for a modern RISC-V multiprocessor using ANSI C.

ACKNOWLEDGMENTS

xv6 is inspired by John Lions's Commentary on UNIX 6th Edition (Peer
to Peer Communications; ISBN: 1-57398-013-7; 1st edition (June 14,
2000)).  See also https://pdos.csail.mit.edu/6.1810/, which provides
pointers to on-line resources for v6.

